TERMINOLOGY TRAP that cost many iterations: when a user asks for the 'scatter version' of water vs the 'refraction version', they may mean the REFLECTIVE SKY SHEEN (the water reading as a reflective surface), NOT the underwater absorption/deep-colour. Confirm the user's mental model early (AskUserQuestion with concrete visual options) instead of assuming 'scatter' = volumetric absorption. The two visible water modes a user distinguishes: (1) REFRACTION = see-through to the seabed (shallow/nadir); (2) 'SCATTER' = reflective sky-sheen surface (deep/grazing). Gate the sky reflection by a DEPTH scalar (reflW = fresnel(grazing) * depthGate) so it is ZERO in shallow water (stays transparent) and ramps in only over deep water -- a user will explicitly say 'the sheen must not affect shallow water'. Earlier over-suppressing the reflection (cap 0.08, tint to sea-blue) to kill a 'milky white' defect ALSO killed this wanted sheen -- the milky-white was the bright sky COLOUR washing everything, fixable by gating reflection to deep water, NOT by removing reflection. Lesson: when stuck re-deriving the same complaint, the defect is usually a vocabulary mismatch -- surface concrete visual options and let the user pick.